 honorably in Limbo. Furthermore, it has long been suggested that for much of the basic framework of the Divine Comedy Dante was indebted to apocryphal traditions about a “night journey” taken by Muhammad.Dante scholars have increasingly returned to the question of Islam to explore the often surprising encounters among religious traditions that the Middle Ages afforded. This collection of essays works through what was known of the Qur’an and of Islamic philosophy and science in Dante’s day and explores the bases for Dante’s images of Muhammad and Ali. It further compels us to look at key instances of engagement among Muslims, Jews, and Christians.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aChristianity and other religionsxIslamxHistory. 0aIslam and literaturexHistory. 0aIslam in literature. 0aIslamxRelationsxChristianityxHistory. 0aIslamic philosophyxIn literature. 4aIslamic Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aMedieval Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Italian.2bisacsh  aDante.  aIslam.  aMuhammad.  aMuslim-Christian.  aNight Voyage.  aOrientalism.  aconvivencia.  ami'raj.1 aAbulafia, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBattistoni, Giorgio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoccassini, Daniela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurman, Thomas E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCantarino, Vicente, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorti, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrank, Maria Esposito, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGázquez, José Martínez, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMallette, Karla, eco